getSqlFromClause

public java.lang.String getSqlFromClause()
Description copied from class: Dto

Get the SQL FROM clause for the Query classes. By default, this is just the SQL table name. For classes that have superclasses, it is a series of JOIN clauses that walk the superclass tree to the root to query all the inherited properties for a leaf class. The returned string has no "FROM" keyword and can be null if the current class is abstract. The table aliases will be the table names. The method handles multiple inheritance. All the superclass tables join to the current class table directly. For example, if you have A, B, and C (C-->B-->A), the FROM clause looks like this: 

 

 

 C AS C JOIN B AS B ON C.aId = B.aId JOIN A AS A ON C.aId = A.aId

The strategy uses the assumption that the subclass inherits the primary key. You must have a set of attributes in the subclass with the same names as the primary key attributes in the superclass, and the value of the attributes must match (foreign key).

Specified by:
getSqlFromClause in class Dto

addSubclassesToFromClause

public java.lang.StringBuilder addSubclassesToFromClause(java.util.List subclasses,
                                                         java.lang.String leafAlias,
                                                         java.lang.StringBuilder fromClause)
Add the subclasses of a specified class to the FROM clause in a string builder instance. The method recursively walks up the tree of subclasses starting from the leaves and adds LEFT OUTER JOIN clauses to the FROM clause.

Specified by:
